2.7.2 Specific Conclusions 
164 As I have noted, Seven's primary case as to the substantial lessening of competition relates to the wholesale sports channel market. 
In Chapter 12 , I find that Seven has failed to establish the existence of that market. 
I also find that Seven has ]n[ established the existence of either the AFL pay rights market ]v[ the NRL pay rights market on which it relies. 
However, I conclude that Seven has made out that there was, at the relevant times, a retail pay television market in the terms pleaded by it. 
165 It follows from the findings made in Chapter 12, that Seven can only succeed in its anti-competitive effects case under s 45(2) of the TP Act if the provisions on which it relies had the effect ]v[ likely effect of substantially lessening competition in the retail pay television market. 
In Chapter 13 , I find that the Master Agreement Provision ]^[ the other provisions relied on by Seven did ]n[ have the effect ]v[ likely effect at the relevant times of substantially lessening competition in that market. 
By December 2000 (when the Master Agreement was entered into) ]^[ January 2001 (when the parties gave effect to the Master Agreement Provision), Optus' pay television operations had been experiencing very substantial losses over a period of several years. 
The strong likelihood in December 2000 ]^[ January 2001 was that, if the Master Agreement had ]n[ been entered into ]v[ implemented, Optus would have negotiated a content sharing agreement with Foxtel along the lines of the Foxtel-Optus CSA (which was in fact executed on 5 March 2002). 
Thus, even in the absence of the Master Agreement Provision, Optus would ]n[ have been a significant constraint on Foxtel in the retail pay television market. 
166 In Chapter 14 , I conclude that Seven's case based on the anti-competitive purpose of the various provisions, including the Master Agreement Provision, cannot succeed. 
By reason of Optus' parlous state, any lessening of competition in that market would have occurred quite independently of the fate of C7. 
167 Although strictly ]n[ necessary to do so, I consider in Chapter 14 further construction questions relating to s 45(2)(a)(ii) ]^[ (b)(ii) of the TP Act . 
I construe these provisions as requiring all parties responsible ]f[ the inclusion of the impugned provision in the contract, arrangement ]v[ understanding to have the subjective purpose of substantially lessening competition, if a contravention of s 45(2) is to be established. 
I find that Telstra was responsible, together with the other Consortium Respondents, ]f[ including the Master Agreement Provision in the Master Agreement (that is, the provision requiring ]v[ contemplating that bids would be made ]f[ both the AFL ]^[ NRL pay television rights). 
But I also find that Telstra did ]n[ have the purpose proscribed by s 45(2), even if it is assumed that the other Consortium Respondents did have such a purpose. 
Thus Seven's purpose case under s 45(2) in relation to the Master Agreement Provision fails. 
168 Seven's case in relation to the other provisions on which it relies (with one exception) similarly fails because Seven cannot show that all parties responsible ]f[ including the provision in the contract, arrangement ]v[ understanding shared the purpose proscribed by s 45(2) of the TP Act . 
The exception is the so-called News-Foxtel Licence, which is ]n[ affected by this particular analysis, although I reject Seven's claim based on the News-Foxtel Licence ]f[ other reasons. 
169 In view of the conclusions reached in Chapter 14, it is ]n[ necessary, in order to deal with Seven's purpose case under s 45(2) of the TP Act , to make factual findings about the purpose of News, Foxtel ]^[ PBL. 
However, such findings may be important if my construction of s 45(2) is incorrect. 
Moreover, the purpose of News, Foxtel ]^[ PBL may be relevant to Seven's case that Foxtel took advantage of its market power ]f[ a proscribed purpose in contravention of s 46(1) of the TP Act . 
