14.1 Scope of Chapter 
2317 This Chapter is primarily concerned with Seven's purpose case against News, Foxtel (Sky Cable ]^[ Telstra Media), PBL ]^[ Telstra (that is, the Consortium Respondents), insofar as it is founded in s 45(2) of the TP Act . 
Seven contends that the Consortium Respondents made contracts ]v[ arrangements, ]v[ arrived at understandings, containing various provisions which had the purpose of substantially lessening competition. 
Seven also alleges that the Consortium Respondents gave effect to the various provisions. 
2318 The Chapter addresses two issues of construction that are important to Seven's case. 
One issue is whether, in order ]f[ a contravention of s 45(2) to be made out by reason of an anti-competitive purpose, all the parties responsible ]f[ including a provision in a contract (including an arrangement ]v[ understanding) must share that purpose. 
If so, Seven's case based on a particular provision (such as the Master Agreement Provision) will fail unless all the parties responsible ]f[ its inclusion in the contract have the purpose of substantially lessening competition. 
2319 The second issue of construction is whether s 45(2) can be contravened where the alleged anti-competitive purpose, even if achieved, could ]n[ have the effect of substantially lessening competition in a market. 
Seven argues that an alleged contravenor can have the proscribed purpose notwithstanding that it is in fact impossible ]f[ the alleged contravenor to achieve the purpose. 
In particular, Seven contends that a party can contravene s 45(2) by having the purpose of substantially lessening competition in a market which it believes exists, even if the market does ]n[ in fact exist. 
2320 The second issue of construction leads to a related question: where a party seeks to achieve a particular objective (such as killing C7), ]b[ that objective, even if achieved, cannot have the effect of substantially lessening competition in a market, does the party have the purpose of substantially lessening competition? 
2321 I commence the Chapter with an explanation of why findings as to the purpose ]v[ purposes of the Consortium Respondents are significant to the issues in the proceedings. 
I then outline Seven's pleaded purpose case under s 45(2) of the TP Act ]^[ address the issues of construction I have identified. 
Since I conclude that a contravention of s 45(2) of the TP Act by reason of an anti-competitive purpose cannot be made out unless all parties responsible ]f[ including the provision in the contract shared that purpose, I consider whether Seven can show that to be the case in relation to each of the provisions upon which it relies. 
That analysis requires findings to be made as to Telstra's purpose. 
I also consider whether, on the findings I have made, the purpose alleged against the Consortium Respondents is one that can be said to involve substantially lessening competition. 
2322 As will appear, it is ]n[ strictly necessary ]f[ me, in addressing Seven's purpose case under s 45(2) of the TP Act , to make findings as to whether the Consortium Respondents, other than Telstra, had the purpose of substantially lessening competition. 
However, findings on that issue will be significant if my analysis in this Chapter is wrong and, in any event, bear on other issues in the case. 
