16.6.3.2 RELIEF 
2758 If this conclusion is wrong and, in making the statements to the AFL, Foxtel took advantage of its market power in contravention of s 46 of the TP Act, an issue arises as to whether Seven is entitled to any relief in respect of that contravention. 
2759 As I have noted, one of the difficulties in a large ]^[ complex case such as this is that submissions as to liability ]^[ relief may have to be made without the parties (or the Court) having the benefit of findings of fact. 
The possible combinations ]^[ permutations in this case are virtually limitless. 
It is therefore ]n[ surprising that Seven does ]n[ appear to have specifically addressed the question of what relief, if any, should flow from a finding that Foxtel's conduct in making statements to the AFL contravened s 46(1) of the TP Act . 
2760 The Statement of Claim is ]n[ clear on the point. 
It alleges that Foxtel's statements to the AFL ' reinforced ' certain consequences flowing from other contraventions of s 46 of the TP Act (par 472). 
They include C7 being prevented from acquiring the AFL pay television rights (par 468). 
It may be that Seven intends to assert that, if the relevant statements had ]n[ been made to the AFL, Seven's bid ]f[ the AFL broadcasting rights (including the pay television rights) would ]v[ might have succeeded. 
2761 If Seven intends to advance such a claim, it cannot succeed. 
The evidence suggests that the AFL's preference ]f[ News' bid over that of Seven had nothing to do with the statements that were made to the AFL. 
It is true that the paper prepared ]f[ the AFL's Broadcasting Negotiating Committee in May 2000 recorded that there was no guarantee that C7 would end up on Foxtel. 
However, there is nothing in the later AFL documentation assessing the competing bids which suggests that the statements played any part in the final decision to award the pay television rights to Foxtel (through News). 
Indeed, there is nothing in the AFL's contemporaneous records to suggest that, as the time ]f[ awarding the rights came closer, the AFL thought that Foxtel would ]n[ take the C7 channels if Seven succeeded in its bid. 
2762 On the contrary, Seven's bid failed because the AFL considered that News was offering a much higher price ]^[ that the other terms of its bid were satisfactory. 
As I have found in Chapter 8, Seven put itself out of the running by ]n[ making its best bid ]f[ the AFL pay television rights and, in that sense, was the author of its own misfortune. 
There was no causal relationship between the statements made by Foxtel to the AFL concerning C7's access to the Foxtel platform ]^[ any loss sustained by Seven. 
2763 In the absence of proof of any compensable loss to Seven, I would ]n[ be disposed to grant declaratory relief in respect of any contravention of s 46 of the TP Act that may have occurred by reason of Foxtel making the statements to the AFL concerning the carriage of C7. 
The contraventions took place some seven years ago and, like ]s[ many other matters in this case, the transactions of which they were part have been superseded by subsequent events. 
Without minimising the importance of any breach of s 46, the contraventions here were ]n[ of major significance ]^[ had no discernible impact on the recipients of the statements. 
Had the Statement of Claim ]n[ added the complaint about the statements to the more serious alleged contraventions of s 46 of the TP Act , the complaints of themselves are unlikely to have warranted the institution of proceedings in this Court. 
According to Seven, the letter of 13 December 2000 conveyed to the NRL Partnership the proposition that Foxtel would ]n[ carry C7 even if Seven won the NRL pay television rights. 
2765 Seven says that a statement to this effect was of particular significance since the amount offered by C7 ]f[ the NRL pay television rights depended on the number of subscribers to the pay television services carrying NRL content. 
2766 Ms Ireland's letter to NRL Ltd must be placed in context. 
It was a reply to Mr Gallop's request ]f[ information concerning the litigation relating to the use of the Telstra Cable . 
The entirety of Ms Ireland's letter, with the possible exception of one sentence, provides information relating to C7's application ]f[ ' retail access ' (to use Seven's term) via the Telstra Cable. 
Seven does ]n[ suggest that any of the information provided by Ms Ireland was inaccurate ]v[ misleading. 
2767 The only part of the letter that relates to C7 being taken on the Foxtel platform (' wholesale access ') is a single sentence, as follows: 
'Under no circumstance can C7 force FOXTEL to include the C7 channels in FOXTEL's channel-line up whether on basic ]v[ in a tier, even if C7 does ultimately gain access to FOXTEL's STUs'. 
2768 When read in context, that sentence merely conveys the proposition that Seven's claim ]f[ compulsory retail access could ]n[ have the consequence that Foxtel could be compelled to take C7 on the Foxtel retail platform. 
That was a perfectly accurate statement and, in my view, carried no implication as to whether ]v[ ]n[ C7 would be taken on the Foxtel Service if C7 succeeded in acquiring the NRL pay television rights. 
2769 Given this interpretation of Ms Ireland's letter, its contents do ]n[ give rise to any issue under s 46(1) of the TP Act . 
The admissions in the Respondents' defences carry Seven's s 46 case no further. 
16.6.5 Aggregation of Conduct 
2770 In view of the conclusions I have reached, there is no basis ]f[ attributing a different character to the totality of the conduct than to its component parts. 
If none of the conduct complained of by Seven constituted a contravention of s 46 of the TP Act , it is difficult to see how the conduct as a whole could constitute such a contravention. 
Indeed, I do ]n[ understand Seven to argue that if its individual claims fail it should nonetheless succeed by reference to the totality of the conduct. 
2771 It follows that Seven's case based on s 46 of the TP Act cannot succeed. 
