18.7.2 Particular Class of Persons 
2892 Although it is ]n[ necessary to decide, I doubt that ' programming suppliers, including the Hollywood studios ' constitute a ' particular class of persons ' within the meaning of s 4D(1)(b) of the TP Act . 
2894 In Rural Press v ACCC the publisher of the Murray Valley Standard agreed to withdraw its threat to distribute the newspaper in the circulation area of the River News in return ]f[ the publisher of the River News agreeing ]n[ to intrude into the Murray Valley Standard's circulation area. 
The trial Judge found that the arrangement had a subjective purpose: 
'of preventing ]v[ restricting ]v[ limiting the supply of services to the particular class ]v[ classes of persons, being those in the Mannum area (or in that area ]^[ extending to a [line] about 40 km north of Mannum) who could otherwise receive the information ]^[ news in the River News ]v[ who could otherwise advertise in the River News ]v[ take advantage of advertising in the River News '. 
2895 The joint judgment of Gummow, Hayne ]^[ Heydon JJ noted (at 89-90 [87]) that there had been little argument in Rural Press v ACCC as to whether there was a lack of particularity in the class of persons identified by the trial Judge, namely ' customers ]^[ potential customers of the River News'. 
Nonetheless, their Honours expressed the view that the class had been adequately defined. 
They pointed out that even if s 4D required the identity of members of the class to be ascertained, it would have been possible to draw up a list of advertisers who had used the River News ]^[ that would have constituted a sufficient class ]f[ the purposes of the section. 
2896 The joint judgment in Rural Press v ACCC 216 CLR, at 90 [88], referred to the judgment of the Full Court of this Court in ASX Operations Pty Ltd v Pont Data Australia Pty Ltd (No 1) (1990) 27 FCR 460. 
In that case, the Full Court suggested that persons may constitute a particular class within the meaning of s 4D of the TP Act , if the distinguishing feature of the class ' is that its members are objects of an anti-competitive purpose ': 27 FCR, at 488, per curiam . 
The joint judgment in Rural Press v ACCC observed (216 CLR, at 90 [88]) that ASX v Pont Data had ]n[ been overruled by the High Court in News v South Sydney . 
Only Callinan J in News v South Sydney had criticised the decision (215 CLR, at 638-639 [217], 640-641 [228]), while McHugh ]^[ Gummow JJ, (the latter of whom had been a member of the Court in ASX v Pont Data ) had accepted it as correct (215 CLR, at 581 [46], 589-590 [74]-[77]). 
The joint judgment in Rural Press v ACCC gave this reason ]f[ ]n[ having to resolve whether ASX v Pont Data had been correctly decided (216 CLR, at 90-91 [88]): 
'In any event, to define a particular class by reference to its geographical location is ]n[ to define it by the fact of its exclusion from supply ]v[ acquisition, because it is identified at the time of the arrangement ]^[ indeed identifiable before that time'. 
2897 Gleeson CJ ]^[ Callinan J, in their concurring judgment in Rural Press v ACCC , clearly favoured a narrower construction of the statutory concept of a class of persons. 
Their Honours reasoned as follows (216 CLR, at 61-63 [5]-[12]): 
'In applying s 4D, courts have had to consider the statutory concept of a provision (of a contract, arrangement ]v[ understanding) which has the purpose of preventing, restricting ]v[ limiting supply to ]v[ acquisition from particular persons ]v[ classes of persons. 
This is a compound concept involving a certain kind of purpose, having as its object particular persons ]v[ classes of persons. 
The particularity of the persons ]v[ classes of persons who are the objects of the purpose as defined ]^[ proscribed is essential to the concept of an exclusionary provision. 
The significance of a finding that a provision is an exclusionary provision within s 4D ]^[ s 45(2)(a)(i) ]^[ (b)(i) is that such a finding engages a per se legislative prohibition. 
It becomes unnecessary to consider whether it has the purpose ]v[ effect of substantially lessening competition in a market. 
If attention were ]n[ paid to the compound nature of an exclusionary provision, ]^[ the requirement of particularity of its object ]v[ objects, there is a danger that s 4D would be given an operation that would greatly reduce the statutory significance of lessening competition, in relation to agreements between competitors generally. 
Contracts, arrangements ]v[ understandings between competitors commonly involve some form of prevention, restriction ]v[ limitation of supply ]v[ acquisition of goods ]v[ services. 
If two hairdressers in a suburban main street were to have an understanding that one would provide services to men, ]^[ one would provide services to women, it may be unlikely that their understanding would involve a substantial lessening of competition in a market. 
It would be surprising if it were held, nevertheless, to contravene the Act. 
To the extent to which it had an anti-competitive purpose, that purpose would ]n[ be "directed toward" particular persons ]v[ classes of persons. 
... 
We agree with Gummow, Hayne ]^[ Heydon JJ that there was sufficient particularity in the present case, ]b[ we can think of other cases in which it would be absent, notwithstanding the existence of a purpose of preventing, restricting, ]v[ limiting supply ]v[ acquisition. 
If it were ]n[ so, the references to particular persons ]v[ classes of persons would be redundant. 
The Full Court referred to the changes that have taken place in the form of s 4D. 
In its original form, the proscribed purpose was of preventing, restricting ]v[ limiting supply to ]v[ acquisition from particular persons. 
The words "or classes of persons" were added in 1986, following some decisions that were thought to reveal an undue narrowness in the legislation it its original form. 
Those words were clearly intended to widen the provision, ]b[ ]n[ to change its entire character. 
The proscribed purpose must still be one that is directed toward particular persons ]v[ classes of persons. 
Parliament did ]n[ delete the word "particular" ]^[ substitute the word "any". 
Nor did it remove all reference to persons as objects of the proscribed purpose. 
The legislative history, as well as the text, tends strongly against a reading of the section which requires only that a provision of a contract, arrangement ]v[ understanding has the purpose of preventing, restricting ]v[ limiting, in any way, supply ]v[ acquisition. 
Supply ]v[ acquisition will always be to ]v[ from persons. 
Ordinary principles of construction require that the references to particular persons ]v[ classes of persons be given work to do; they are ]n[ mere drafting verbosity. 
A court construing a provision in an Act "must strive to give meaning to every word of the provision". 
A court will seek to avoid a construction of a statute that renders some of its language otiose. 
Here, that consideration is powerfully reinforced by the legislative history, which shows that the reference to particular persons was originally an essential feature of s 4D, ]^[ that the addition of the reference to classes was intended to expand it, ]n[ to make it superfluous. 
... 
An exclusionary provision may be directed toward particular persons ]v[ classes of persons without necessarily having a purpose of injuring ]v[ disadvantaging them. 
However, a purpose of the kind defined ]^[ proscribed must exist, ]^[ must be directed toward particular persons ]v[ classes of persons, ]f[ the legislative prohibition to apply'. 
Their Honours did ]n[ refer to ASX v Pont Data 27 FCR, at 488, ]b[ it is difficult to reconcile their reasoning with that decision. 
2898 The facts of the present case differ from Rural Press v ACCC , in that the class of persons at whom the CSA Provisions are said to be directed is ]n[ defined by reference to geographical location. 
The ' class ' here is defined by reference to a limitation imposed by the CSA Provisions on the acquisition of programming: that is, the class consists of all programming suppliers, anywhere in the world, whose products ]^[ services Foxtel ]^[ Optus are prevented from attempting to acquire in competition with each other. 
The application of s 45(2) (read with s 4D), if otherwise satisfied, therefore appears to turn on whether the Full Federal Court's statement of principle in ASX v Pont Data 27 FCR at 488, is correct. 
2899 It is a brave, ]n[ to say foolish, trial judge who ventures unnecessarily into dangerous waters in which swirl differing ]b[ non-binding views of members of the High Court. 
I shall therefore only say, without expressing a final view, that the opinion expressed by Gleeson CJ ]^[ Callinan J in Rural Press v ACCC appears, with respect, to have considerable force. 
If that opinion represents the correct construction of s 4D, Seven has ]n[ established that making the Foxtel-Optus CSA, ]v[ giving effect to the CSA Provisions, was directed at a class of persons within the meaning of s 4D of the TP Act . 
18.8 Conclusion 
2900 Seven has ]n[ made out its case based on the purpose, ]v[ effect ]v[ likely effect, of provisions in the Foxtel-Optus CSA. 
In particular, I conclude that Seven has ]n[ shown that the purpose ]v[ effect of the relevant provisions was to substantially lessen competition in the retail pay television market. 
