That this is the statutory objective does ]n[ necessarily mean, however, that the techniques adopted in the present case involved a contravention of cl 10(1)(e) of Pt 6 of Sch 2 to the BS Act . 
3327 Seven's written submissions do ]n[ make clear the precise time at which Foxtel Cable is said to have acquired the rights to broadcast the Foxtel exclusive matches. 
The Statement of Claim merely pleads that Foxtel sub-licensed the AFL pay television rights to Foxtel Cable (par 512), without specifying when this occurred. 
3328 As best I can make out, Seven's case appears to be that Foxtel Cable acquired the rights to the Foxtel exclusive matches shortly after the execution of the last of the Foxtel Put (14 December 2000), the AFL-News Licence (19 December 2000) ]^[ the News-Foxtel Licence (about 25 January 2001). 
At that time, Foxtel Cable (in the language of cl 10(1)(e)) acquired the right to televise, on a subscription television broadcasting service, an event that is specified in a notice under s 115(1) of the BS Act . 
The ' event ' comprised the three Foxtel exclusive matches, which were included within the anti-siphoning list. 
Seven says that if Foxtel Cable acquired its right to televise the AFL exclusive matches at a time when no free-to-air broadcaster had the right to televise the event, Foxtel was in breach of cl 10(1)(e). 
3329 Seven's case makes the assumption that it is irrelevant that the three Foxtel exclusive matches to be shown on pay television could ]n[ be precisely identified until Nine ]^[ Ten had made their selection of five free-to-air matches in each round. 
(Pursuant to cl 6 of each of the Nine Put ]^[ Ten Put, these selections had to be made by Nine ]^[ Ten six weeks in advance of each round of matches. 
) Although the assumption is disputed by News, I proceed on the basis that it is also correct. 
3331 Seven says that the relevant question is whether ' in respect of the acquisition by Foxtel Cable ... of the rights to televise AFL matches on ... Foxtel ', free-to-air broadcasters had the ' right ' to televise those matches within the meaning of the BS Act . 
Seven submits that where the relevant right (by which Seven means the right of the free-to-air broadcasters): 
'(a) is subject to an understanding ]v[ agreement that it will ]n[ be exercised; and/or 
(b) is subject to the payment of a financial penalty which is ]s[ disproportionate to the value of the live broadcast right to FTA that it has the effect of preventing the exercise of the "right", 
then the relevant commercial television broadcasting licensee ]v[ licensees are subject to a sufficient fetter that they do ]n[ have the "right to televise the event" within the meaning of the [BS Act]'. 
21.1.3.2 AN UNDERSTANDING AS ALLEGED? 
3332 In the particulars to the Statement of Claim, Seven states that the understanding upon which it relies is implicit in the fact that Nine ]^[ Ten had to pay $500,000 ]f[ each Foxtel exclusive match broadcast within 14 days of the day on which the match was played. 
In its Closing Submissions, Seven does ]n[ base its case simply on the terms of the various licences, ]b[ relies on a number of documents to establish the existence of the pleaded understanding. 
3333 In my view, these documents do ]n[ establish that there was an understanding that neither Nine nor Ten would exercise their respective contractual rights to broadcast live the Foxtel exclusive matches upon payment of a fee of $500,000 per match. 
The understanding ]s[ far as Nine was concerned was that embodied in the AFL-News Licence ]^[ the Nine Put: that is, that if Nine exercised its rights in respect of any of these matches it would pay $500,000. 
In my opinion, the position was the same in relation to Ten. 
3334 None of the Respondents' witnesses was specifically asked about the understanding alleged by Seven. 
In particular, none was asked whether it was understood that neither Nine nor Ten would exercise its contractual right to broadcast Foxtel exclusive matches upon payment of $500,000 per match, even if there were sound commercial reasons ]f[ them to do so. 
An exchange with Mr Philip took place as follows: 
'[MR SUMPTION:] But you do accept that each of [the proposed sub-licensees] appreciated that they were participating in a broader arrangement negotiated by News involving a share-out of rights between three identifiable parties? 
