The assumption underlying this contention is that a ' disproportionate ' payment that must be which a party must make if it exercises a right to televise a sporting event live, in effect negates the existence of that party's ' right to televise the event ' within the meaning of cl 10(1)(e) of Pt 6 of Sch 2 to the BS Act . 
Again, I proceed on the basis that this assumption is correct, although it is ]n[ necessarily free from difficulty. 
3338 Seven's submissions do ]n[ make it clear how the proportionality of what it describes as the ' penalty ' ]f[ broadcasting the Foxtel exclusive matches is to be assessed. 
As News points out, there may be aspects of free-to-air broadcasting that make the rights to matches very valuable ]f[ reasons that are ]n[ easy to quantify precisely in monetary terms. 
In particular, the value of a given match ]v[ series of matches may ]n[ merely be reflected in a mathematical calculation derived from the general contractual arrangements entered into ]f[ the AFL free-to-air ]v[ pay television rights. 
